[[Category:位階制度|しようはちい]]

{{No footnotes|date=2015th year 8月}}
'''Shōhachi-i''' (正八位) is one of the {{ill|Court Ranks of Japan|ja|位階|12=draft|12=draft}}. It is positioned below {{ill|Junior Seventh Rank|ja|従七位|1=Junior Seventh Rank|12=draft|12=draft}} and above {{ill|Junior Eighth Rank|ja|従八位|1=Junior Eighth Rank|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref>https://www.wakapoetry.net/background/society/court-offices-titles-and-ranks/court-ranks/</ref>
In the {{ill|Ritsuryō system|ja|律令制|12=draft|12=draft}}, Shōhachi-i was further divided into two subranks: Upper Shōhachi-i (正八位上) and Lower Shōhachi-i (正八位下). During the early {{ill|Meiji period|ja|明治時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, under the {{ill|Daijōkan system (Meiji period)|ja|太政官制|12=draft|12=draft}}, these subranks were eliminated. Shōhachi-i corresponded to positions such as assistant scribes (権少史) in the {{ill|Jingikan|ja|神祇官|1=Department of Divinities|blank= (明治時代)|12=draft|12=draft}} and chief clerks ({{ill|Shuki|ja|主記|12=draft|12=draft}}) in the {{ill|Daijōkan|ja|太政官 (明治時代)|12=draft|12=draft}}.
Under the honor system established by the {{ill|Joi Jōrei|ja|叙位条例|12=draft|12=draft}} (Imperial Edict No. 10 of 1887) and the {{ill|Ikai-ryō|ja|位階令|12=draft|12=draft}} (Imperial Edict No. 325 of 1926), Shōhachi-i was the rank immediately above the lowest rank, {{ill|Jūhachi-i|ja|従八位|1=Junior Eighth Rank|12=draft|12=draft}}, in the hierarchy of {{ill|Court Ranks of Japan|ja|位階|12=draft|12=draft}}.
