{{No footnotes|date=2015th year 8月}}
'''Shōhachi-i''' (正八位) is one of the {{ill|Court Ranks of Japan|ja|位階|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. It is positioned below {{ill|Junior Seventh Rank|ja|従七位|1=Junior Seventh Rank|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and above {{ill|Junior Eighth Rank|ja|従八位|1=Junior Eighth Rank|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref>https://www.wakapoetry.net/background/society/court-offices-titles-and-Ranks/court-Ranks/</ref>
In the {{ill|Ritsuryō system|ja|律令制|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Shōhachi-i was further divided into two subRanks: Upper Shōhachi-i (正八位上) and Lower Shōhachi-i (正八位下). During the early {{ill|Meiji period|ja|明治時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, under the {{ill|Daijōkan system (Meiji period)|ja|太政官制|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, these subRanks were eliminated. Shōhachi-i corresponded to positions such as assistant scribes (権少史) in the {{ill|Jingikan|ja|神祇官|1=Department of Divinities|blank= (明治時代)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and chief clerks ({{ill|Shuki|ja|主記|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) in the {{ill|Daijōkan|ja|太政官 (明治時代)|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
Under the honor system established by the {{ill|Joi Jōrei|ja|叙位条例|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Imperial Edict No. 10 of 1887) and the {{ill|Ikai-ryō|ja|位階令|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Imperial Edict No. 325 of 1926), Shōhachi-i was the Rank immediately above the lowest Rank, {{ill|Jūhachi-i|ja|従八位|1=Junior Eighth Rank|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, in the hierarchy of {{ill|Court Ranks of Japan|ja|位階|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
